translate:
A slight thought, a touch of feeling, so vast and unconfined;
In this life, I reside in a mountain monastery, lacking much.
Old age accompanies me as I fish with Hou Xi, our paths intertwined;
Together we witness the tides of the river, as Lu Can joins our ride.
I have cultivated my spirit through the teachings of Mencius;
I long to seek fame and office, as I ask about Yan.
Sometimes I read letters from home, warm and comforting;
I tidy up the dusty books, brushing away the white moths that hide.

Writing on the clouds and splitting silkworm cocoons, creating an image of Lan Ting;
The brushes and fan handles are created by the children of the floating village.
Brightly following the rules, donating the moon's axe;
Clearing and eliminating the heat, sharing the peach flute together.
Within the celestial path, the jade hair rides the phoenix;
In the ice mirror, the ink poet serves as a gentleman.
Cherishing the winter for convenience, using it as a mirror;
Warding off coldness and comforting each other in the camp.

In every hearing, I cultivate within, and gaze upon the crow;
Regretfully asking the short-lived cicadas about spring and autumn.
In mundane matters, I still remain, but with a lighthearted attitude;
Within my ancient heart, I pursue my own humble goals.
Bound by the shallow fields in the land of Yue, like a gourd tied to a tree;
I labor for my rent, as if crossing the copper bridge with two carp.
My white hairs begin to grow, and my travels taste of solitude;
I seek glory and elegance, visiting the ascetic saints along the way.

Determined to advance without fear, he ranks among the best.
Compared to the united flight, his skills are unparalleled.
At the tip of the pen, he summons the words of wisdom;
Within the skin, he conceals the essence of autumn.
Earnestly serving as an assistant, he accepts the honor;
In the imperial court, he pursues the distant aspirations.
With sorrow and sadness, he pays homage to the departed;
In the golden hall, he looks forward to glory and excellence.

Reckless and straight, I have no experience in the world;
Thunder god descends from the nine heavens to scold me.
Facing the wind and snow for three months, my horse avoids battles for four times.
Burning wood with snow, I share my meager provisions;
Buying wine at an alehouse to comfort my hunger and thunder.
I hear that tomorrow I will ascend the Min Mountains;
The spring breeze fills my heart as it blows through the thatched cottage.

In the thatched cottage, we speak through the night and spring emerges; 
Curtain and screen are low, the garden is shrouded in water vapor. 
I sit coldly, my heart like iron, admiring your poetry so high; 
You have the energy of a cloud, while I am like a piece of iron. 
On the mountain peak, we should gather ferns together; 
Outside the city, there is no field for me to cultivate alone. 
Let's fill our cups with wine and get drunk wildly; 
Our children's whispers need not disturb our joy.

In solitude, I lie in the northern window, master of poetry;
Therefore, my pen should be lowered, as the scholars bow.
With a laugh, I sweep away the vines and vines, their value high;
Once revered in the palace halls, our voices echo.
Throughout the six realms, we shall return to our pens;
Together, we shall enjoy the clear river once again.
There need be no fuss or trouble, as our blades glide through;
At night, we drink from countless vats, without restraint.

In the spring half, the flowers compete for the sky's fragrance; 
Red and white, they vie for the best scent on earth. 
There is no place for this scene in human world; 
It belongs to the morning star, a testament of its beauty. 
The morning star rides the wind, descending to the heavens; 
Through bright windows, ancient and modern books are well-read. 
At the tip of the pen, spring appears everywhere; 
Among literature and ink, the three-cornered tiger roams. 
Today, its value soars like the clouds and smoke; 
Its influence should be passed down through the ages. 
We will pursue our family legacy and share prosperity; 
With the nation, we will enjoy a million years of peace.

After the wild wind passes, the sky is cleansed like a wash; 
Four volumes of dark clouds fill the vast expanse of miles. 
At the third watch of the night, the moonlight shines coldly on the high tower; 
Fish songs echo through the cold reeds, responding to each other. 
A cup of wine is shared with the exiled immortal, 
Discussing literature with waves crashing and words flowing smoothly. 
In the middle of the night, I gently brush my clothes and am about to depart; 
My wandering enthusiasm soars with the autumn clouds. 
A small boat cuts through the waves, asking you, where do you intend to go? 
With a heart and mind open to the narrow gorges and vast oceans, 
I want to see the endless expanses of the vast Ming Sea. 
I still study in the academy, living a simple life; 
How can I transform into a cloud and follow the dragon? 
I have not yet fulfilled my desire to appreciate the beautiful scenery; 
Please take me in your silk pouch, carrying me along.

In the fierce north wind, a thousand cracks whisper;
Dark clouds lie low, ready to release flying snow.
Drunkenly riding on a leaf-like glass, suddenly the dark clouds disperse in the night moonlight.
On the Phoenix Mountain, I contemplate the great enlightenment;
Barefoot and with a bamboo staff, I play with clear springs.
My heart finds verses from the spring scenery, scattered into the vegetation and rising smoke.
How I wish to enjoy this night, chatting and laughing;
Hastily creating new words for the coming year.
I realize now that I am not the same as before;
I shall pursue the wind and rain by burning candles.

Hasty messages and stars race, violent guests arise;
In the west, watch towers' smoke stretch for hundreds of miles.
At midnight, we shout in fear and find a fishing boat;
Old and young, three hundred hands intertwine.
Incoherently twisted like a snake, we break through the thatch;
Suddenly, the wind blows, lifting our bodies high.
On the sandy shore, there is little solace to be found;
A thousand measures of sorrow are washed away in vain.
Recalling those days when I served the Jade Emperor;
Night watches at the palace walls, the faucet flows on.
Who would have thought that we would be driven so swiftly?
Restless, we sleep in the land of clouds and waters.
Formerly, my donkey braved the blazing fire;
Now, this small boat floats on top of the remaining snow.
Through hot summers and cold winters, we desire a rest;
The drums and gongs sound, as if the earth were to split.
Where can we find a wise dragon to lie in wait?
Upholding the heavens' governance relies on Mr. Lu.
Who will urgently call forth the heroes of the world?
Let me sing of the Yao dynasty's virtues with my horn.

Lanyae groves on the shore, thunder and lightning frighten; 
Raging storm and torrential rain, as if to overturn the sea. 
In the water and stones, we make our intentions clear; 
Our original aspirations do not change with the weather. 
Realization is like being unenlightened; 
Hengshan does not know to disperse the clouds. 
Lu Yang's attempt to brandish his sword is unnecessary; 
Guo Tai can still wear his corner hat. 
A monk guides me in my flight, 
To see the master's path to enlightenment. 
Hot springs bubble, a taste returned; 
Through centuries, the streams do not flow east. 
I laugh at my teacher's greatness, 
Causing spirits to spy on my tracks. 
How can I be free from divine understanding? 
The cliffs still have the white dragon flying.

Fulfilling all my desires, I'm tired of worldly affairs;
What is my life's purpose now that I return?
The woodcutter who found the broken chesspiece suspects there's no way out;
The hanging kettle master has a wondrous home.
At night, the golden ripples of the water reflect the moonlight on the osmanthus trees;
In the autumn wind, the snow flurries embrace the reeds.
The cold fish refuse to swallow the bait;
As the excitement fades, the clear songs turn into a journey.

Vaguely wandering, I haven't settled yet; 
Farewell the mountain dweller once again. 
Wild geese shadows form words in the water, 
Clouds hover like guests on the river. 
Together we reside, regardless of distance; 
A thousand miles apart, we are still neighbors. 
Deep emerald leaves adorn one branch, 
Decaying red blooms fill five baskets. 
Returning the journey, I ascend the bird path; 
Gentle woods and the spring of my ancestral home.

Insect-covered branches, the wind whispers restlessness; 
At night, I ponder the old star in the sky. 
My heart longs to return to tend mother's flowers; 
A thousand miles away, we seek each other like ducks. 
Red maple trees with golden leaves falling; 
Rushes of yellow leaves float on the water. 
The beautiful West Mountain bathes in autumn rain; 
Rolling up the curtains, we share the distant hue.

In the enchanting mountain range, I've never been to such a sublime place; 
With my keen interest in traveling lightly, I forget the rough paths. 
Who doesn't need a cane for support, as we share this moment with the hermit? 
Together, we admire the lush greenery and the shady trees lining the banks. 
We venture to the west of the creek, seeking a fire to boil our tea; 
Through the bamboo groves, we hear the sound of zithers and prayer beads from the hermitage.
